# The Bar of Northern Ireland  

The Bar of Northern Ireland is the professional association of [barristers](/Barrister) for [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland), representing more than 600 members. Its headquarters occupy the historic [Bar Library](/Bar_of_Northern_Ireland) on 91 Chichester Street in [Belfast](/Belfast), a building that also houses the [Bar Council of Northern Ireland](/Bar_of_Northern_Ireland) (the statutory regulatory body for the Northern Irish Bar) and the Executive Council. The organisation functions as both a representative and a regulatory body, safeguarding professional standards, providing continuing education, and fostering networking among its members. [¹] [²]  

The Executive Council has assumed many of the duties formerly performed by the [Benchers](/Bencher) of the Inn of Court of Northern Ireland, an institution founded at a joint meeting of the Bench and Bar on 11 January 1926. [³]  

---  

## Relationship with the Bar of Ireland  

The Bar of Ireland, based in [Dublin](/Dublin), historically served as the sole professional body for all barristers on the island of [Ireland](/Ireland). Following the [Government of Ireland Act 1920](/Government_of_Ireland_Act_1920), which partitioned Ireland into two distinct legal jurisdictions, the political and legal landscape shifted dramatically after 1922, when Northern Ireland emerged as a separate jurisdiction with its own courts and bar. [4] [5] [6]  

Initially, the [King's Inns](/King%27s_Inns) in [Dublin](/Dublin) hoped that partition would not diminish its all‑island remit; it therefore created a “Committee of Fifteen” comprising Northern Ireland benchers in 1922. [7] However, the committee pressed for greater autonomy, and on 11 January 1926 the Inn of Court of Northern Ireland [8] and the Bar Council of Northern Ireland were formally established. [9]  

Since then, the Bar of Northern Ireland has maintained a collaborative relationship with its counterpart, the Bar of Ireland, particularly through joint initiatives such as the [Irish Rule of Law International](/Irish_Rule_of_Law_International). The two bodies co‑hosted the 2024 World Bar Conference, underscoring a shared commitment to the rule of law across the island. [10] [11] [12]  

Practitioners may move freely between the two jurisdictions: members of the Bar of Northern Ireland are eligible for membership of the Bar of Ireland without additional examinations, and vice‑versa. [13]  

---  

## Development of the Bar of Northern Ireland  

The profession of barrister in what is now [Ireland](/Ireland) traces its roots to the arrival of the common‑law system in the 12th century, co‑existing with the native [Brehon law](/Brehon_law) until its gradual abolition in the 17th century. [14] [15]  

In 1541, the Honorable Society of [King's Inns](/King%27s_Inns) was founded on the site of the present Four Courts, providing the first formal training venue for Irish barristers. Although students were required to keep terms at one of the English [Inns of Court](/Inns_of_Court) in [London](/London), this arrangement proved costly and contentious until the Barristers’ Admission (Ireland) Act 1885 abolished the mandatory English term‑keeping. [14]  

Throughout the 18th century, regulation of the bar intensified. The Benchers of the Honorable Society of [King's Inns](/King%27s_Inns) acted as the de‑facto governing body, wielding powers to censure or disbar members. The early 19th century saw the creation of the Law Library Society in February 1816, a subscription‑based repository of legal texts that would become a hallmark of the Irish Bar, allowing barristers to study and reference statutes collectively rather than from private chambers. [14]  

The General Council of the Bar of Ireland was formed after a meeting of the Irish Bar in 1897, establishing a more organised representation for the profession. [17] [18]  

From 11 January 1926 onward, the Inn of Court of Northern Ireland [8] and the Bar Council of Northern Ireland were created, marking the formal birth of a distinct Northern Irish legal profession. [9] The current constitution, adopted on 5 October 1983, continues to govern both the Bar of Northern Ireland and the Bar Council, outlining their respective powers and responsibilities. [6]  

For many decades the Inn of Court of Northern Ireland existed largely as a theoretical body, lacking the physical spaces for social interaction that its counterparts in [London](/London) and [Dublin](/Dublin) enjoyed. This changed dramatically with the redevelopment of the Bar Library, officially reopened by [Her Excellency](/Her_Exellency) [Professor Mary McAleese, The President of Ireland](/Mary_McAleese) on 29 April 2005. The refurbishment introduced modern library facilities, dedicated rooms for [Continuing Professional Development](/Continuing_Professional_Development), meeting spaces, and venues for dining and receptions, finally giving the Northern Irish Bar the professional environment it had long lacked. [19]  

---  

## Barristers' chambers  

Unlike many common‑law jurisdictions, [Ireland](/Ireland) does not maintain a formal system of [barristers' chambers](/Barristers%27_chambers). Instead, most barristers in Northern Ireland practice from a shared [Bar Library](/Bar_of_Northern_Ireland) premises, paying a subscription for the right to use the common facilities. [14] [20]  

Historically, however, there were attempts to establish a chambers system. Until 1885, aspiring Irish barristers were required to keep terms at an English Inn of Court before being called to the [Bar of Ireland](/Bar_of_Ireland). During the 19th century, the Benchers of the [King's Inns](/King%27s_Inns) even drafted plans to construct chambers on Henrietta Street in Dublin, allocating land and imposing annual deposits on new barristers and solicitors to fund the venture. Architect [James Gandon](/James_Gandon) raised practical objections concerning the simultaneous construction of the main King's Inns building, and the chambers project was ultimately abandoned. [21] [22]  

To this day, neither Northern Ireland nor the [Republic of Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland) has developed a traditional chambers model. The shared‑library approach remains the norm, fostering a collaborative rather than competitive environment among barristers. [23]  

