## Notable barristers  

- **[Frances "Fay" Kyle](/Frances_Kyle)** was the first woman to be called to the Bar of Ireland (and indeed to any bar in the United Kingdom or Ireland). Born in [Belfast](/Belfast) in 1893, she earned a BA in French from [Trinity College Dublin](/Trinity_College_Dublin) in 1914 and an LLB in 1916. After commencing studies at the [King's Inns](/King%27s_Inns) in Dublin in January 1920, she was called to the Bar of Ireland on 1 November 1921 and began practising on the Northern Ireland circuit the following year. [24] [25] [26] [27] [28]  

- **[Denis Henry](/Denis_Henry)** was called to the Bar of Ireland in 1885 and subsequently became the inaugural [Lord Chief Justice of Northern Ireland](/Lord_Chief_Justice_of_Northern_Ireland) after the partition of Ireland in 1921.  

- **[Mary McAleese](/Mary_McAleese)** was born in [Belfast](/Belfast) and called to the Bar of Northern Ireland in 1974. After a distinguished legal career in Belfast, she entered politics, serving as the [President of Ireland](/President_of_Ireland) from 1997 to 2011. [29]  

- **[Donal O'Donnell](/Donal_O%27Donnell)** was born in [Belfast](/Belfast) and called to the Bar of Northern Ireland in 1989 (and to the Bar of Ireland in 1982). He later rose to the bench, being appointed a judge of the [Supreme Court of Ireland](/Supreme_Court_of_Ireland) in 2010 and Chief Justice of Ireland in 2021. [30]  

- **[Edward Carson](/Edward_Carson)**, a renowned orator and unionist politician, began his professional life as a barrister after being called to the Bar of Ireland in 1877. [31] [32]  

These figures illustrate the Bar of Northern Ireland’s profound impact on both the legal profession and the broader political landscape of the island.  

