## Distinction between senior counsel and king's counsel  

[Senior counsel](/Senior_counsel) and [king's counsel](/King%27s_counsel) denote the same honour: recognition of a barrister’s expertise and experience through elevation to the Inner Bar. [33] [34] The terminology differs by jurisdiction; the United Kingdom and several Commonwealth realms use “King’s Counsel,” whereas other jurisdictions, including Northern Ireland, traditionally use “Senior Counsel.”  

In Northern Ireland, barristers who are called to the Inner Bar receive the title “King’s Counsel.” This has sparked debate among some members who object to the monarchical reference and to the legacy of the [Partition of Ireland](/Partition_of_Ireland), which places the British monarch as head of state for Northern Ireland. [36] In 2003, a compromise was engineered by Philip Magee, a barrister practising across both jurisdictions. Magee was designated senior counsel in the Republic of Ireland while simultaneously retaining the privileges of a king’s counsel in Northern Ireland, based on confirmation from the Lord Chief Justice of Northern Ireland. [37] [38]  

Only Northern Irish barristers who are also members of the Bar of Ireland and who meet the experience criteria for the Inner Bar in the Republic of Ireland can pursue this pathway. [39] [40]  

Historically, barristers in Northern Ireland were required to swear an oath to serve the British monarch upon elevation to the Inner Bar. This requirement proved contentious for those who opposed monarchy or partition. In 1997 the Bar of Northern Ireland voted to seek removal of the oath, arguing that “no other profession requires its practitioners, on admission or advancement, to promise expressly to serve the interests of the Crown as opposed to the interests of potential clients.” [41] [42] By 2000 the oath was revised to read: “well and truly serve all whom I may lawfully be called upon to serve in the office of one of Her/His Majesty’s Counsel.” [43]  

